{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3167761,"name":"java4first","username":"java4first","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/6bbea6/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-03-19T13:33:03.201Z","cooked":"<p>Hi -</p>
<p>I have a question about another 2023 WPILib change where a method went away (maybe it never worked - but we were using it), and I‚Äôm wondering if anyone knows the equivalent way to do it this year.</p>
<p>I would like to hold the initialization of all the robot code until we get access to the driver station data, as we use dynamic class loading at initialization, and it (used to) take settings from the dashboard to do so.  (I realize it‚Äôs possible to do it differently, but would like to try and get back to our old approach).</p>
<p>Here is the method as it worked in previous years (up until this year) - the particular method that went away is ‚ÄúisNewControlData()‚Äù. I tried looking through the source for the DriverStation and couldn‚Äôt seem to find anything equivalent ‚Ä¶</p>
<p>Thanks in advance!<br>
Stu</p>
<blockquote>
<p>/**<br>
* Holds the constructor until we receive at least one update of the control<br>
* data, which holds the run-time configuration.<br>
**/<br>
private void waitForDriverStationData() {<br>
long count = 0;<br>
while (!DriverStation.isNewControlData()) {<br>
if ((count % 100) == 0) {<br>
logger.trace(‚ÄúWaiting ‚Ä¶‚Äù);<br>
}<br>
try {<br>
Thread.sleep(100);<br>
} catch (InterruptedException ex) {<br>
logger.error("exception for sleep: ", ex);<br>
}<br>
count++;<br>
}<br>
}</p>
</blockquote>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":12,"updated_at":"2023-03-19T13:34:01.994Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":30,"reads":187,"readers_count":186,"score":197.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":430824,"topic_slug":"hold-robotinit-until-driver-station-data-arrives","display_username":"java4first","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":14762,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/hold-robotinit-until-driver-station-data-arrives/430824/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3167778,"name":"Fletch","username":"Fletch1373","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png","created_at":"2023-03-19T14:03:43.347Z","cooked":"<p>I‚Äôm interested to see what youre actually doing that requires this‚Ä¶ a rearchitecture of that bit of code might be necessary.  Generally speaking, you never want potentially-unbounded loops like that in robot code.  If i were starting a project and ran into the need to dynamically change implementation like that, I might do it in robotPeriodic and hide it behind an ‚ÄúisInitialized‚Äù flag so I know it only runs once and before anything else runs.  If it needs to be able to change dynamically at any point, then i could either remove the flag check, or make it more event-based (depending on how the settings are being transferred over the network, this might be super easy or a bit more difficult).</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":12,"updated_at":"2023-03-19T14:03:43.347Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":169,"readers_count":168,"score":48.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":430824,"topic_slug":"hold-robotinit-until-driver-station-data-arrives","display_username":"Fletch","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":9105,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades"},"post_url":"/t/hold-robotinit-until-driver-station-data-arrives/430824/2","custom_user_title":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1},{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3167780,"name":"Ryan Blue","username":"Ryan_Blue","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/ryan_blue/{size}/174016_2.png","created_at":"2023-03-19T14:05:42.600Z","cooked":"<p><s>You can check for <code>DriverStation.isDSAttached();</code>. This doesn‚Äôt do exactly what you want but I imagine it could get you close enough.</s><br>
